text.tspan: data1 is the previous data buffer. Data2 is the most recent data buffer.,
pre_trig_spike_samps, post_trig_spike_samps specify recorded waveform width
threshold (1 by n_chan) is the voltage threshold, timeout_samps is the requested refractory period post spike peak,
n_chans is the number of channels in the input data.
A data cursor begins at "startpoint" in the input data,
Does any channel cross that channel's threshold
If so, appended all channels, this sample, to peak_vals output
sample points from pre_trig_spike_samps:1:post_trig_spike_samps are appended to waveforms
MODE B: "Threshold then move to local max"
Does any channel cross that channel's threshold?
Find channel with highest value at datacursor samp. On this chan, compare this value to prev
value and next value. If it is local max, save here, otherwise move cursor forward, eval is it
local max? If so, save waveforms centered at this new data cursor, if not... etc
MODE C: "Start with local maxima, keep threshold crossing ones"
Sweep data cursor until it finds a local maximum on any channel. Does that local maximum cross
threshold? If so, save all channels centered on the data cursor.
Then data cursor is moved ahead by either 1 or timeout_samps (whichever greater).
Data cursor position is checked, if it's greater than "stoppoint", return outputs. If it's less than
or equal to stoppoint, return to beginning (check this point for threshold crossing.
ISSUE 1: What is Startpoint? What is stoppoint?
Constraint 1: We can't use any threshold crossings that are so close to data1 left or data2 right
that we have no waveform data for them.
Constraint 2: We don't want to double-count spikes (which may happen, since we see each data
buffer twice in two consecutive calls to the fn.
ISSUE 2: How long should each data buffer be?
Constraint 1: We don't want to drop any spikes (it's possible if the buffers are too small - combined
they may be shorter than the requested spike recording width, or meeting constraints 1&2 from issue 1,
Constraint 2: The frequency at which this fn gets called may be a bottleneck for detecting spikes. Long
buffers take time to fill, takes longer to report spikes.
